    <h2 id="why-vitamin-e-skin">Why Your Skin Depends on Vitamin E Antioxidant Protection</h2>

    <p>Every day, your skin faces an onslaught of oxidative stress — UV radiation generates reactive oxygen species (ROS) in the epidermis, environmental pollutants create free radicals on the skin surface, and normal cellular metabolism produces hydrogen peroxide and superoxide that must be neutralized. Vitamin E (primarily alpha-tocopherol) serves as the skin's primary fat-soluble antioxidant defense, embedded in the lipid bilayer of every cell membrane where it intercepts and neutralizes lipid peroxyl radicals before they can damage cellular structures, DNA, and the collagen matrix that provides skin's structural firmness.</p>

    <div class="key-stat">
      <span class="key-stat-num">50%</span>
      <p class="key-stat-txt">reduction in skin vitamin E levels after UV exposure. A single session of sun exposure depletes epidermal vitamin E by up to 50%, <strong>leaving skin cells vulnerable to oxidative damage during the most critical exposure period.</strong> Oral vitamin E supplementation replenishes this antioxidant reservoir, maintaining the skin's ability to neutralize UV-generated free radicals during and after sun exposure.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The mechanism is precise: when a UV photon strikes a skin cell, it generates a free radical (an unstable molecule with an unpaired electron) that initiates a chain reaction of lipid peroxidation — each damaged lipid molecule creates another free radical, cascading through the cell membrane. Alpha-tocopherol donates a hydrogen atom to the lipid peroxyl radical, converting it to a stable molecule and breaking the chain reaction. The resulting tocopheroxyl radical is then regenerated back to active vitamin E by vitamin C (ascorbic acid), creating a continuous recycling antioxidant system that provides sustained protection as long as both vitamins are available.</p>

    <p>Beyond free radical neutralization, vitamin E inhibits UV-induced prostaglandin and leukotriene formation — inflammatory mediators responsible for sunburn redness, swelling, and the chronic low-grade inflammation (inflammaging) that accelerates visible skin aging. Vitamin E also protects the lipid matrix of the stratum corneum — the skin's outermost barrier layer — maintaining moisture retention and preventing transepidermal water loss (TEWL) that leads to dry, dull skin. This barrier-protective function is why vitamin E deficiency manifests as dry, rough, easily irritated skin.</p>

