    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Vitamin E Gummies for Skin</h2>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How does vitamin E benefit skin?</summary><p>Primary fat-soluble antioxidant in cell membranes. Neutralizes UV-generated free radicals, stops lipid peroxidation chain reactions, reduces UV-induced inflammation, and protects the skin barrier's lipid matrix. Works synergistically with vitamin C.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>What is the best form of vitamin E for skin?</summary><p>Natural d-alpha-tocopherol (2x bioactivity vs. synthetic dl-alpha). Mixed tocopherols (alpha + gamma + delta) provide broadest coverage. Gamma-tocopherol neutralizes nitrogen radicals that alpha cannot. Check label: "d-" = natural, "dl-" = synthetic.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much vitamin E should I take for skin health?</summary><p>100-400 IU of natural d-alpha-tocopherol daily. RDA is 15mg (22 IU). Upper limit is 1,000mg (1,500 IU). Most skin studies use 200-400 IU. Combine with vitamin C and take with fat-containing meals for maximum absorption.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Does vitamin E help with scars and dark spots?</summary><p>Evidence is mixed. Oral vitamin E supports general skin healing via antioxidant protection. For scars and dark spots specifically, retinoids, vitamin C serums, and niacinamide have stronger clinical evidence. Topical vitamin E may cause contact dermatitis in some individuals.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take vitamin E with other beauty supplements?</summary><p>Yes. Best combinations: E + C (antioxidant recycling), E + selenium (glutathione peroxidase support), E + collagen (protects collagen from oxidation), E + omega-3 (barrier support). Separate E and iron by 2 hours (absorption interference).</p></details>

